# 1. Abstract

The rapid evolution of digital health technologies, coupled with advancements in deep learning and natural language processing, has created an unprecedented opportunity to develop intelligent, integrated healthcare platforms that transcend the limitations of conventional clinical information systems. This project presents MediFlow-AI, a comprehensive web-based healthcare platform built upon the MERN (MongoDB, Express.js, React.js, Node.js) technology stack, tightly integrated with an independent Python-based Artificial Intelligence microservice for automated medical image analysis, clinical decision support, and knowledge-grounded patient interaction.

The AI subsystem of MediFlow-AI employs a novel dual-architecture ensemble strategy that combines DenseNet-121 (optimized for texture analysis) and ResNet-50 (optimized for structural analysis) for multi-label chest X-ray classification across fourteen distinct thoracic pathologies. These image-derived features are fused with structured clinical metadata — including patient demographics, vital signs, and symptom profiles — through a learned multimodal embedding. A Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM) module generates interpretable heatmaps localized to the primary diagnostic finding, providing visual explanations for clinical users. Beyond radiographic analysis, the platform incorporates a Graph Retrieval-Augmented Generation (Graph-RAG) pipeline, backed by a Neo4j knowledge graph and Sentence-BERT embeddings, enabling patient-specific conversational medical assistance grounded in ingested clinical reports. A Gemini Vision Large Language Model serves as a third panelist in a consensus-based triage workflow, providing free-text clinical synthesis.

The healthcare workflow modules encompass role-based access control for patients, doctors, and superadministrators, appointment management with Jitsi-based video consultation, digital prescription creation with e-signature capture, an integrated pharmacy with Razorpay payment processing, laboratory test scheduling, clinical report generation in SOAP format, and an audit logging system. The decoupled microservice architecture ensures independent scaling, fault isolation, and technology-agnostic deployment. Experimental evaluation indicates that the max-confidence ensemble strategy achieves superior recall for critical pathologies compared to naive probability averaging, while the triaged risk-scoring mechanism provides clinically meaningful urgency stratification. The system demonstrates that tightly coupling production-grade full-stack engineering with deep learning inference can yield a unified, scalable, and clinically responsible healthcare platform suitable for real-world triage assistance.

**Keywords:** MERN Stack, Deep Learning, Ensemble Learning, DenseNet-121, ResNet-50, EfficientNet-B0, Chest X-Ray Classification, Multimodal Fusion, Grad-CAM, Graph RAG, Neo4j, Knowledge Graph, Healthcare Platform, Clinical Decision Support, Retrieval-Augmented Generation, Medical Image Analysis, FastAPI, Microservice Architecture.

