# 3. Literature Survey

## 3.1 AI in Medical Image Classification

The application of deep convolutional neural networks to medical image classification has yielded substantial advances in diagnostic accuracy over the past decade. The seminal work by Rajpurkar et al. (2017) introduced CheXNet, a DenseNet-121-based model trained on the ChestX-ray14 dataset, which achieved radiologist-level performance in pneumonia detection with an F1 score exceeding 0.435 on the test partition. CheXNet demonstrated that transfer learning from ImageNet pretraining, combined with dense connectivity patterns, could effectively capture the subtle textural patterns associated with pulmonary consolidation. However, CheXNet operates as a single-task binary classifier limited to pneumonia versus normal classification. In real-world clinical settings, a single chest radiograph may exhibit multiple simultaneous pathologies — such as concurrent pleural effusion and cardiomegaly — rendering single-label classification clinically inadequate. Furthermore, CheXNet does not incorporate clinical metadata beyond the image itself, ignoring the rich contextual information that clinicians routinely use during diagnostic reasoning [8].

Wang et al. (2017) introduced the ChestX-ray8 (later expanded to ChestX-ray14) dataset, which remains one of the most widely used benchmarks for thoracic pathology classification. The dataset contains over 112,000 frontal-view chest X-ray images from more than 30,000 unique patients, annotated with fourteen disease labels extracted from radiology reports using natural language processing. While this dataset has catalyzed significant research progress, it suffers from label noise arising from the automated extraction process and from the predominantly North American patient demographics, which may limit model generalization across ethnically and geographically diverse populations.

Irtaza et al. (2024) advanced the field by proposing a multi-label lung disease classification system utilizing ensemble learning techniques on chest X-ray datasets. Their ensemble approach combined predictions from multiple trained models to improve overall diagnostic accuracy, achieving high Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (AUC) scores across multiple pathology categories. However, the ensemble methodology incurred substantial computational overhead due to the necessity of running inference through all member models and aggregating results, rendering it impractical for real-time deployment in resource-constrained clinical environments where inference latency directly impacts clinical workflow efficiency [4].

Usman et al. (2024) implemented a DenseNet-121-based multi-label classification model trained on the ChestX-ray14 dataset, achieving competitive per-pathology AUC scores. Their work demonstrated the effectiveness of dense connectivity for multi-label thoracic classification but acknowledged two significant limitations: dataset bias attributable to the demographic composition of ChestX-ray14, and limited generalization performance when evaluated on radiographs from populations not represented in the training data [5].

Nguyen et al. (2022) introduced the VinDr-CXR dataset, a large-scale annotated chest X-ray corpus sourced from two major Vietnamese hospital systems, providing crucial geographic and demographic diversity to the medical imaging research community. The dataset annotates fourteen local-level diagnostic labels (including pneumonia, cardiomegaly, pleural effusion, pneumothorax, atelectasis, consolidation, lung opacity, nodule/mass, infiltration, fibrosis, pleural thickening, calcification, and other lesion) with radiologist-consensus annotations obtained through a two-reader protocol. However, residual label noise arising from inter-annotator disagreement and the dataset's dual-institution but single-country provenance continue to limit external validity [6].

## 3.2 Retrieval-Augmented Generation in Healthcare

The application of Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) to clinical natural language processing has emerged as a promising paradigm for knowledge-grounded medical question answering. Lewis et al. (2020) introduced the foundational RAG framework for knowledge-intensive NLP tasks, which combines a parametric language model with a non-parametric retrieval component to ground generated text in factual evidence retrieved from a knowledge corpus. The RAG architecture demonstrated strong performance on open-domain question answering benchmarks including Natural Questions and WebQuestions. However, the original RAG architecture was designed for general-domain applications and lacks the safety filtering mechanisms essential for clinical deployment, where incorrect or misleading information could directly harm patient outcomes. The absence of medical reliability constraints and domain-specific retrieval optimization limits its direct applicability to healthcare contexts [7].

Amugongo et al. (2025) conducted a comprehensive systematic review of RAG applications in healthcare Large Language Model (LLM) systems, synthesizing findings from peer-reviewed publications across multiple medical subdomains. The review identified retrieval quality, clinical validation, and regulatory compliance as the three principal barriers to real-world deployment of RAG-based healthcare systems. The authors concluded that while RAG shows substantial promise for improving clinical decision support, no existing RAG-based healthcare system satisfactorily addresses all three challenges simultaneously. The review specifically highlighted the need for structured knowledge representations (such as knowledge graphs) to complement unstructured retrieval, a finding that directly motivates the Graph-RAG approach adopted in MediFlow-AI [1].

Zhao et al. (2025) proposed MedRAG, a Knowledge Graph-enhanced RAG framework for healthcare applications that integrates Neo4j-based graph reasoning with dense retrieval over medical corpora. Their evaluation on the MedQA and PubMedQA benchmarks demonstrated accuracy improvements of 5–8% over baseline RAG configurations, attributable to the structured reasoning capabilities provided by the knowledge graph. Despite these promising results, MedRAG was evaluated exclusively on public medical QA benchmarks and lacks validation with real patient data. Furthermore, the system does not integrate with clinical imaging workflows or electronic health record systems, limiting its practical applicability in clinical environments [2].

## 3.3 Integrated Healthcare Platforms

Rossi et al. (2025) explored the integration of AI capabilities into telemedicine platforms for remote healthcare delivery. Their comprehensive analysis demonstrated that AI-enhanced telemedicine systems could improve diagnostic accessibility in underserved regions, reduce consultation wait times, and provide preliminary diagnostic screening that assists clinicians. However, the study identified several persistent challenges that hinder the practical deployment of such systems: system fragmentation across diagnostic and workflow modules creating data silos, algorithmic bias in AI models trained on non-representative datasets producing disparate performance across demographic groups, and regulatory uncertainty regarding the clinical deployment and liability implications of AI-generated diagnoses [3].

The MERN (MongoDB, Express.js, React.js, Node.js) technology stack has gained significant traction in healthcare system development due to its unified JavaScript ecosystem enabling isomorphic development, scalable NoSQL data storage via MongoDB's document-oriented architecture, and component-based frontend design via React enabling responsive single-page applications. However, the existing literature on MERN-based healthcare platforms largely treats the web application and AI components as loosely coupled subsystems, with limited attention to the architectural patterns necessary for reliable, low-latency AI inference within clinical workflows.

## 3.4 Explainable AI in Medical Imaging

Interpretability of AI predictions is a critical requirement for clinical adoption, as regulatory bodies and clinical practitioners require transparent reasoning behind automated diagnostic decisions. Selvaraju et al. (2017) introduced Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM), a technique that leverages the gradients flowing into the final convolutional layer to produce coarse localization maps highlighting diagnostically relevant regions in the input image. Grad-CAM's architecture-agnostic nature makes it applicable to any CNN-based model without requiring architectural modifications. Subsequent work has applied Grad-CAM to chest X-ray analysis to provide visual explanations complementing classification outputs. However, the integration of Grad-CAM outputs into production clinical triage interfaces — alongside ensemble consensus views and quantitative risk stratification — remains underexplored, with most implementations limited to offline research visualization in Jupyter notebooks or standalone scripts.

## 3.5 Summary and Research Gap Identification

The comprehensive literature survey reveals the following critical gaps that the proposed MediFlow-AI platform seeks to address:

| Gap ID | Description | Addressed By |
|--------|-------------|--------------|
| G1 | Absence of unified diagnostic-workflow integration in existing platforms | Unified MERN + AI architecture with direct triage-to-prescription workflow |
| G2 | Limited multi-architecture ensemble strategies (homogeneous ensembles, naive averaging) | Max-confidence ensemble combining DenseNet-121 and ResNet-50 |
| G3 | Disconnected multimodal analysis (image-only classification) | Learned clinical embedding branch fusing vital signs and symptoms |
| G4 | Absence of patient-specific knowledge-grounded conversational AI | Graph-RAG pipeline with Neo4j, Sentence-BERT, and patient-scoped retrieval |
| G5 | Insufficient clinical explainability in production interfaces | Grad-CAM heatmaps, risk scoring, and consensus panel in triage UI |

